<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 253px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Add-ins for the Authoring Software</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p>The authoring software's specific add-ins for formwork quantification analyze structural elements such as beams, columns, slabs, and walls, reporting their surface area.&nbsp;</p>
<p>To prevent material waste and potential negative cost impacts, it's crucial to consider the interaction between structural elements during the quantity takeoff process, ensuring alignment with actual construction techniques.&nbsp;</p>
<p>This interaction-based approach is exemplified in "Scenario 02" of Figure 03.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/53934/plan-content/1709312336177_ad66939c-e885-4726-89f0-eb175f6a2c41.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=eqm945X147KQ5YP4DunIU4MivINjeIWsgNvbCCDkLClYRlzRqd1kV4MSV0P9fe~-IJC2qSD-ahShOsAk53x2JLgD2coTn7pThDtFiXZNmFfiKrHktKvg4yHbO8r8XAEfgSjag3hYuDzNcncrxGiKzsTjkuOZRR2AYEEPCy0RlO0zE8u~UaYWY5Cw6wzXdYgwV~rxSUQkM01bPUBL7sUu3fkmhwZInQfGqiAQ0ltr7W8qsTGV14pwN9c7u~LIXYN5m62NZyXUtX3FHgTFfuzIOsAmqJdDrTsOovHx5tgVtqPG346PD-PS1CFUAJo3nU7o75znyya-69NIAu37qkX~pA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" class="fr-fic fr-dii" style="width: 692px;"></p>
<p><em>Figure 03. - Illustration of surface area-based (derived) quantity takeoff with Dynamo. While scenario 01 quantifies all sides and bottom faces of the elements, disregarding their elements' intersections, scenario 02 represents these relationships being considered.</em></p>
<p>Some commercial solutions on the market calculate surface area by deducting intersected parts from other elements.&nbsp;</p>
<p>This data is then computed and added to each instance as a new parameter.</p>
<p>Either way, the quantification should follow the construction methodology and be clearly described in the BoQ.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>